WEBVTT

00:01.000 --> 00:08.166
♪

00:08.166 --> 00:10.750
GREG: And with the press
of this button,

00:10.750 --> 00:13.166
you are now
on Facebook.

00:13.166 --> 00:14.959
I don’t feel
any different.

00:14.959 --> 00:16.542
You will,
because now you’ll be able

00:16.542 --> 00:18.542
to see pictures of Lark
the day that we take ’em.

00:18.542 --> 00:19.583
Yeah, instead
of telling us

00:19.583 --> 00:21.500
to print them out
every week, which is fun.

00:21.500 --> 00:23.792
Well, we tried loading ’em
on the digital,

00:23.792 --> 00:25.500
uh, picture frame there,

00:25.500 --> 00:28.291
but it’s still showing
the kid it came with.

00:28.291 --> 00:30.208
GREG: So that explains
why your friends

00:30.208 --> 00:32.041
are always confused
when they meet Lark.

00:32.041 --> 00:33.583
Yeah. Uh-huh.

00:33.583 --> 00:35.000
Okay, so, first,

00:35.000 --> 00:36.667
all you need to do
is enter your hometown.

00:36.667 --> 00:38.125
No, no, no, no.

00:38.125 --> 00:40.083
That’s how they find you

00:40.083 --> 00:42.917
and then that’s how
they steal your identity.

00:42.917 --> 00:44.667
Pretty sure that’s
not how that works,

00:44.667 --> 00:46.166
but we can circle back to it.

00:46.166 --> 00:48.583
Um, okay, next thing--
really easy--

00:48.583 --> 00:51.291
-just click on me or Greg...
JOAN: Greg.

00:51.291 --> 00:54.709
Okay. And, uh, then you
can see our pictures.

00:54.709 --> 00:57.583
JOAN: Oh, look at
that little cutie!

00:57.583 --> 00:59.291
Yeah, I’m wearing that
hat that you gave me.

00:59.291 --> 01:00.875
And--and holding Lark.

01:00.875 --> 01:02.125
This is really something.

01:02.125 --> 01:04.417
-And you can make comments.
-Yeah.

01:04.417 --> 01:07.000
"I’m going
to get a sandwich."

01:07.000 --> 01:08.667
Well, the point of
Facebook is more to,

01:08.667 --> 01:10.500
like, have a dialogue
with other people.

01:10.500 --> 01:12.625
JOHN: Oh. Yeah. Got it.

01:12.625 --> 01:16.250
"Anyone else
getting a sandwich?"

01:16.250 --> 01:18.625
Oh. Tim’s coming over.

01:18.625 --> 01:20.542
-Wants some of your sandwich.
-Oh, no.

01:20.542 --> 01:22.500
♪

01:22.500 --> 01:24.917
Wow, your mom liked
every single photo

01:24.917 --> 01:28.667
I posted on Facebook and
then commented, "I like that."

01:28.667 --> 01:29.792
(awkward chuckle)

01:29.792 --> 01:31.375
Well, now that they get
to see Lark every day,

01:31.375 --> 01:32.792
they don’t have
to come over.

01:32.792 --> 01:35.208
It’s a pretty genius move
on my part, if you ask me.

01:35.208 --> 01:36.542
JEN: Oh, and, look,

01:36.542 --> 01:38.542
They invited me
to play<i> PetVille.</i>

01:38.542 --> 01:40.041
Oh, no.
I invited you to<i> PetVille.</i>

01:40.041 --> 01:41.333
Yeah, I’m the mayor.

01:41.333 --> 01:43.333
My cat-stituency
just voted me in,

01:43.333 --> 01:45.792
and the Itty Bitty Kitty
Committee ratified it.

01:50.625 --> 01:52.458
We need to talk.

01:52.458 --> 01:55.125
♪

01:55.125 --> 01:57.625
I can’t get
into the Facebook.

01:57.625 --> 01:59.542
I can’t remember
my password.

01:59.542 --> 02:01.333
That’s what you...

02:01.333 --> 02:02.500
-Uh-huh.
-Okay.

02:02.500 --> 02:03.417
(chuckles)

02:03.417 --> 02:05.083
All right, well, uh,
it’s the same password

02:05.083 --> 02:06.333
you have
for all your stuff, Dad.

02:06.333 --> 02:08.375
-Yeah.
JOHN: She made me change it.

02:08.375 --> 02:09.792
-Why would you do that?
JOAN: I--I heard you--

02:09.792 --> 02:11.792
that you have to change it
every three hours.

02:11.792 --> 02:13.417
Yeah, then I had
to change it again

02:13.417 --> 02:15.542
because it wanted
a capital letter.

02:15.542 --> 02:18.041
And then again
because it wanted a number.

02:18.041 --> 02:20.333
Then it called me weak,
and I just walked away.

02:20.333 --> 02:22.083
Okay, everybody,
let’s just calm down.

02:22.083 --> 02:23.417
These things happen. Okay?

02:23.417 --> 02:24.709
I’ll just reset
the password.

02:24.709 --> 02:26.125
-Yeah.
-Okay?

02:26.125 --> 02:28.667
But will the new password
work over at our house?

02:28.667 --> 02:30.333
Yeah. Yeah,
it’ll work everywhere.

02:30.333 --> 02:31.834
Well, what about
Tim and Heather’s?

02:31.834 --> 02:33.542
JEN: Mm-hmm. Yeah,
that counts as everywhere.

02:33.542 --> 02:34.709
And Matt and Colleen’s?

02:34.709 --> 02:37.959
Yeah, their computer’s one
of those flat little slickies.

02:37.959 --> 02:39.417
Yeah, no, there, too.

02:39.417 --> 02:40.625
Even on my phone?

02:40.625 --> 02:41.625
What about my phone?

02:41.625 --> 02:43.583
JEN: This is a super
fun game. Both phones.

02:43.583 --> 02:45.041
JOAN: What about Tim
and Heather’s phone?

02:45.041 --> 02:46.458
Uh, hey, Greg, you want
to start fielding

02:46.458 --> 02:48.000
-some of these?
GREG: Yeah, well, I would,

02:48.000 --> 02:49.542
honey, but I’m
kind of knee-deep

02:49.542 --> 02:51.083
in this whole
password thing.

02:51.083 --> 02:53.166
Once it’s on my phone,

02:53.166 --> 02:56.625
how do I get it
over to my computer?

02:56.625 --> 02:58.083
WOMAN: You can’t go in there.
You need an appointment.

02:58.083 --> 02:59.291
JOAN: We’re family.

02:59.291 --> 03:01.291
JOHN: Plus, it’s
a legal emergency.

03:01.291 --> 03:03.125
Hi. What is going on?

03:03.125 --> 03:04.583
Well, we’re hoping
you can tell us.

03:04.583 --> 03:07.000
Who is Miriam Bickle?

03:07.000 --> 03:09.542
My high school
physics teacher who tried

03:09.542 --> 03:12.041
to sell everyone jewelry
made out of dried pasta.

03:12.041 --> 03:14.375
JOHN: Yeah, Facebook said
she’s your friend.

03:14.375 --> 03:16.709
Yeah. And she wants
to be our friend,

03:16.709 --> 03:18.500
and we don’t know why.

03:18.500 --> 03:21.333
Is she a cyberbully?

03:21.333 --> 03:25.375
Okay. Um, was Greg not around
to answer this question?

03:25.375 --> 03:27.000
Oh, we didn’t want
to bother him at work.

03:27.000 --> 03:30.125
He was in the Dream Lab
thinking of inventions.

03:30.125 --> 03:31.041
JEN: Oh.

03:31.041 --> 03:33.041
JOHN: We saw it
on his status update.

03:33.041 --> 03:34.250
Okay.

03:34.250 --> 03:35.542
Well, um, first of all,

03:35.542 --> 03:37.583
you should be friends
with Miriam Bickle.

03:37.583 --> 03:38.667
Really, you should
be friends

03:38.667 --> 03:40.917
with anyone who sends you
a request at this point.

03:40.917 --> 03:42.125
But most importantly,

03:42.125 --> 03:44.583
you should
never be afraid

03:44.583 --> 03:47.417
to bother Greg
in his Dream Lab.

03:47.417 --> 03:48.625
-Wow.
JEN: Which I also call

03:48.625 --> 03:50.333
the garage.

03:50.333 --> 03:51.333
♪

03:51.333 --> 03:53.750
(indistinct chatter)

03:56.166 --> 03:59.375
JEN: Uh, who are
all these people?

03:59.375 --> 04:01.625
Did we just walk
into an intervention?

04:01.625 --> 04:02.834
Look, I swear,
whatever my parents

04:02.834 --> 04:03.750
are mad at you about,

04:03.750 --> 04:05.041
I will stand
by your side.

04:05.041 --> 04:06.750
What? Why do you
assume it’s me?

04:06.750 --> 04:08.667
-Jen!
JEN: Oh, my God, it is me.

04:08.667 --> 04:11.125
MIRIAM: It’s Miriam Bickle.

04:11.125 --> 04:13.083
Mrs. Bickle.

04:13.083 --> 04:14.250
My pastor was right.

04:14.250 --> 04:16.291
People do care about me.

04:16.291 --> 04:17.333
(chuckles)

04:17.333 --> 04:20.917
Oh. Um, will you excuse
us for one minute?

04:20.917 --> 04:22.959
It’s so nice
to see you.

04:22.959 --> 04:24.125
Please help us.

04:24.125 --> 04:25.500
What is going on?
Why did you invite

04:25.500 --> 04:26.834
all these people
to brunch?

04:26.834 --> 04:29.041
We didn’t.
I think Facebook did.

04:29.041 --> 04:31.208
JOAN: Yes, I thought I was
just inviting my group,

04:31.208 --> 04:34.875
but apparently my group
includes all of my patients,

04:34.875 --> 04:38.166
the book club,
the mall walkers’ meet-up,

04:38.166 --> 04:41.792
the librarian, and
the pizza delivery man.

04:41.792 --> 04:43.834
Hey, Greg, I just met
your high school girlfriend.

04:43.834 --> 04:45.625
GREG: What?
TIM: Man,

04:45.625 --> 04:47.000
she’s so easy to talk to.

04:47.000 --> 04:48.333
You know,
she’s a therapist now,

04:48.333 --> 04:49.166
just like
your mom.

04:50.875 --> 04:52.375
What a coincidence, right?

04:52.375 --> 04:53.458
Is it?

04:53.458 --> 04:55.458
-Erica.
JOAN: I don’t like this.

04:55.458 --> 04:58.375
I wish we could go back
to simpler times,

04:58.375 --> 05:01.000
when we had
our plug-in picture frame

05:01.000 --> 05:04.166
with our digital
Asian grandson.

05:04.166 --> 05:06.917
Remember how happy
he was at Christmas?

05:06.917 --> 05:07.834
JOHN:
That’s it.

05:07.834 --> 05:08.834
No more Facebook.

05:08.834 --> 05:10.166
No, no, no, no,
no, no, no, no.

05:10.166 --> 05:12.333
Guys, this is
just a speed bump

05:12.333 --> 05:14.750
on your social
media adventure.

05:14.750 --> 05:17.834
(phones chiming)

05:17.834 --> 05:18.750
Oh. Hey, guys.

05:18.750 --> 05:22.375
Mom, listen, I think your
Facebook account was hacked.

05:22.375 --> 05:23.583
I knew it.

05:23.583 --> 05:24.709
TIM: All right, Joan,
I’ll bite.

05:24.709 --> 05:27.000
What’s the new superfood
that melts belly fat?

05:27.000 --> 05:29.625
No! Don’t open that.
That’s not me.

05:29.625 --> 05:31.709
My identity’s
been stolen!

05:31.709 --> 05:35.083
I think I found
your first suspect.

05:35.083 --> 05:37.375
SOPHIA: It’s uncanny.
HEATHER: Oh, Erica’s here.

05:37.375 --> 05:40.125
Yeah. Erica’s here.

05:41.125 --> 05:43.333
♪

05:43.333 --> 05:44.458
HEATHER: Hey, carpool karaoke

05:44.458 --> 05:46.542
was pretty fun
this morning, huh?

05:46.542 --> 05:49.250
Yeah. Maybe next time
you’ll let me have a turn.

05:49.250 --> 05:51.083
HEATHER: Eh, probably.
Whoa, whoa. Hey, what?

05:52.500 --> 05:54.083
This is good here.

05:54.083 --> 05:55.041
What?

05:55.041 --> 05:57.458
You don’t need
to walk me in anymore.

05:57.458 --> 05:58.458
HEATHER: Well...

06:01.959 --> 06:02.875
That’s cool!

06:02.875 --> 06:03.834
No, that’s great!

06:03.834 --> 06:06.000
That way, we can just
use the drop-off lane,

06:06.000 --> 06:09.166
and then we save precious
primp time in the morning!

06:13.125 --> 06:14.417
Ha!

06:14.417 --> 06:16.333
♪

06:16.333 --> 06:17.250
(gasps)

06:17.250 --> 06:18.333
Oh.

06:18.333 --> 06:19.959
Oh, Derek.

06:19.959 --> 06:22.208
Oh, no.

06:22.208 --> 06:26.083
Oh, dude, you look like me
after my 40th birthday party.

06:26.083 --> 06:28.417
Not good.

06:28.417 --> 06:30.375
Okay, okay. Come on,
don’t leave me, don’t leave me.

06:30.375 --> 06:32.291
Not you, too. Come on...

06:32.291 --> 06:34.709
Oh. Oh, oh.
Well, that was gross.

06:34.709 --> 06:39.458
♪

06:39.458 --> 06:40.625
-Hey, Mom.
HEATHER: Oh. Sweetie,

06:40.625 --> 06:41.542
I need your help.

06:41.542 --> 06:42.792
Listen, I’ve changed
Derek’s water,

06:42.792 --> 06:44.583
I balanced the pH,
and I’ve cleaned his tank,

06:44.583 --> 06:46.250
but he’s still swimming
on his side.

06:46.250 --> 06:48.417
TYLER: Gotcha. Well, uh,
I can distract Sophia

06:48.417 --> 06:50.709
while you go to the pet store
and do the old switcheroo.

06:50.709 --> 06:53.500
No, no, no. This is
a very special fish, honey.

06:53.500 --> 06:55.583
Sophia and I won him
at the winter festival.

06:55.583 --> 06:56.750
And it was
the first time she ever won

06:56.750 --> 06:58.417
a carnival game
without cheating.

06:58.417 --> 07:00.208
And then we brought him home
in a plastic baggie

07:00.208 --> 07:02.291
and she fell asleep
with her head on my shoulder.

07:02.291 --> 07:04.041
I have to save this fish.

07:04.041 --> 07:05.750
For Sophia.

07:05.750 --> 07:07.500
Yes. For Sophia.

07:07.500 --> 07:09.166
You know, I had a bird
that got sick once,

07:09.166 --> 07:10.959
so I gave him
some cough syrup.

07:10.959 --> 07:13.542
The point is,
don’t give him any cough syrup.

07:13.542 --> 07:15.542
-Oh, yeah.
CLEMENTINE: Mm-hmm.

07:15.542 --> 07:18.083
♪

07:18.083 --> 07:23.125
Okay. How can we help
Derek Hughes today?

07:23.125 --> 07:24.667
Oh.

07:24.667 --> 07:25.917
Derek’s a fish.

07:25.917 --> 07:27.542
He’s not eating.
Can you help him?

07:29.458 --> 07:31.083
Wait. Am I on<i> Vet Pranks?</i>

07:31.083 --> 07:32.959
Where is Dave Coulier?
I love that show.

07:32.959 --> 07:34.417
Hey, did you see the one
where someone brought in

07:34.417 --> 07:36.166
just a horse’s ass?

07:36.166 --> 07:38.125
No. I missed that one.

07:38.125 --> 07:40.000
Well, we’ve got it
up on the website.

07:40.000 --> 07:41.834
Oh. It might cheer you
up after this fish dies.

07:43.417 --> 07:45.375
Oh, uh, sorry.

07:45.375 --> 07:47.667
Um, well, uh...

07:47.667 --> 07:48.959
I suppose you could
try feeding him

07:48.959 --> 07:50.166
with an eyedropper.

07:50.166 --> 07:51.834
-Okay.
-Uh, just keep in mind

07:51.834 --> 07:54.291
an eyedropper will cost
more than a new fish.

07:55.875 --> 07:56.875
Good luck.

07:56.875 --> 08:01.834
♪

08:01.834 --> 08:03.375
Oh, my God, he’s eating.

08:03.375 --> 08:04.834
(gasps)

08:04.834 --> 08:06.375
Derek.

08:06.375 --> 08:07.500
Oh, my God.

08:07.500 --> 08:09.959
♪

08:09.959 --> 08:12.125
TIM: Which brings us to your
informed consent paperwork.

08:12.125 --> 08:13.875
Now, this just details
all the risks involved

08:13.875 --> 08:15.333
in a routine tonsillectomy.

08:15.333 --> 08:17.834
I’m gonna need you to sign
all the marked areas there.

08:17.834 --> 08:19.625
I’m gonna leave you
with that for a second.

08:19.625 --> 08:20.834
This is Dr. Tim Hughes.

08:20.834 --> 08:22.625
I did it; I saved Derek.

08:22.625 --> 08:23.875
Derek. Who’s that again?

08:23.875 --> 08:25.500
Sophia’s fish.

08:25.500 --> 08:26.500
Oh, right. Yeah.

08:26.500 --> 08:28.083
He didn’t look good
last time I saw him.

08:28.083 --> 08:29.542
HEATHER:<i> I know,</i>
<i>it took me all day</i>

08:29.542 --> 08:31.834
and a very expensive
vet bill,

08:31.834 --> 08:33.667
-but I did it.
TIM:<i> You’re so nice.</i>

08:33.667 --> 08:34.834
I would have
just let him die.

08:34.834 --> 08:37.333
HEATHER:<i> No, no, no.</i>
<i>Nobody’s dying on my watch.</i>

08:37.333 --> 08:39.250
Yeah. Well, sometimes
you got to let them die

08:39.250 --> 08:40.709
when you’ve got
a dinner reservation.

08:40.709 --> 08:43.000
No. You don’t
ever let them die.

08:43.000 --> 08:43.959
TIM:<i> I hear that. </i>

08:43.959 --> 08:45.750
I don’t want to bury
another one in the backyard.

08:45.750 --> 08:46.667
HEATHER:<i> I have</i>
<i>to feed him again.</i>

08:46.667 --> 08:47.709
TIM: Okay.

08:47.709 --> 08:49.291
All right, Mrs. Torres.

08:52.792 --> 08:54.166
Mrs. Torres?

08:54.166 --> 08:55.875
♪

08:55.875 --> 08:57.834
SOPHIA: Hey, Mom. I think
there’s something wrong

08:57.834 --> 08:59.041
with Derek.

08:59.041 --> 08:59.959
What?

08:59.959 --> 09:03.625
♪

09:03.625 --> 09:04.667
Oh. Hey, how’s Derek?

09:04.667 --> 09:05.583
Can we see him?

09:05.583 --> 09:06.750
TIM: I’m sorry
to have to be the one

09:06.750 --> 09:08.333
to tell you this,
but Derek...

09:09.709 --> 09:11.041
...is no longer with us.

09:11.041 --> 09:12.709
Oh.

09:12.709 --> 09:14.583
Oh, sweetie,
I am so sorry.

09:14.583 --> 09:18.583
♪

09:18.583 --> 09:20.166
Anybody want to say
any last words

09:20.166 --> 09:22.125
before we send Derek
to the big toilet bowl

09:22.125 --> 09:23.667
in the sky?

09:27.375 --> 09:29.458
Sometimes you don’t know
how good something is

09:29.458 --> 09:32.041
until you don’t
have it anymore.

09:32.041 --> 09:34.083
It’s gonna be okay, Mommy.

09:35.375 --> 09:37.875
♪

09:37.875 --> 09:40.417
(crying)

09:40.417 --> 09:43.709
♪

09:43.709 --> 09:45.417
Honey,
it’s just a fish.

09:45.417 --> 09:47.709
I know.

09:47.709 --> 09:49.125
Bye, Derek.

09:49.125 --> 09:50.667
(toilet flushes)

09:50.667 --> 09:56.000
SARAH MCLACHLAN:
♪<i> I will remember you </i>♪

09:57.333 --> 10:02.041
♪<i> Will you remember me? </i>♪

10:03.709 --> 10:07.583
♪<i> Don’t let your life </i>♪

10:07.583 --> 10:10.917
♪<i> Pass you by </i>♪

10:10.917 --> 10:12.792
♪

10:12.792 --> 10:16.083
♪<i> Weep not for ♪</i>

10:16.083 --> 10:17.250
Whoa-ho!

10:17.250 --> 10:21.291
SARAH MCLACHLAN:
<i>♪ The memories ♪</i>

10:21.291 --> 10:22.458
(toilet flushes)

10:24.083 --> 10:25.792
Could you guys get out now?
I have to poo.

10:25.792 --> 10:26.709
Okay.

10:26.709 --> 10:28.083
♪

10:28.083 --> 10:30.125
JOAN: An elementary school?
COLLEEN: Yeah.

10:30.125 --> 10:32.375
Every little girl dreams
of her perfect wedding,

10:32.375 --> 10:34.250
and a spot like this is
slightly better than nothing,

10:34.250 --> 10:35.083
so it’s perfect.

10:37.875 --> 10:40.000
♪

10:40.000 --> 10:42.792
NED: This is going to be
the wedding of your dreams.

10:42.792 --> 10:45.125
I can barely contain
my excitement.

10:45.125 --> 10:47.291
I can’t imagine
how you two feel.

10:47.291 --> 10:48.542
Mainly confused.

10:48.542 --> 10:50.500
NED: I know it’s unorthodox
for a funeral planner

10:50.500 --> 10:52.125
to also be in
the wedding biz,

10:52.125 --> 10:54.625
but I take great joy
in seeing the happiness

10:54.625 --> 10:56.458
on the faces
of my clients

10:56.458 --> 10:58.417
without having
to paint them on myself.

10:58.417 --> 11:01.583
Oh, here. I brought
my dream wedding look-book.

11:01.583 --> 11:04.125
Everything I’ve had in
mind for the perfect day.

11:04.125 --> 11:05.083
NED: You didn’t
have to bring that.

11:05.083 --> 11:06.959
I held on to yours
from last time.

11:06.959 --> 11:09.917
Whoa. Last time.

11:09.917 --> 11:11.333
NED: She’s our first
guest of honor

11:11.333 --> 11:13.291
to ever be
a repeat customer,

11:13.291 --> 11:16.083
which explains why
I’m so giddy right now.

11:16.083 --> 11:17.709
I’m sorry. Is this
the same funeral planner

11:17.709 --> 11:19.125
you used for your
wedding to Chad?

11:19.125 --> 11:21.417
I’m sorry, but I’ve been
dreaming of my wedding

11:21.417 --> 11:22.792
since the first grade.

11:22.792 --> 11:24.333
I can’t just let all that go.

11:24.333 --> 11:26.500
Letting go
is a part of life, dear.

11:26.500 --> 11:28.500
I, uh, I, uh,
I--I can’t. I can’t.

11:28.500 --> 11:30.750
I can’t be the
groom in a wedding

11:30.750 --> 11:32.333
that wasn’t meant for me.

11:32.333 --> 11:35.458
Meaning isn’t always found
on this earth, son.

11:35.458 --> 11:37.709
Oh. Okay.

11:37.709 --> 11:39.667
You know what?
You’re right. This is silly.

11:39.667 --> 11:42.041
There is no reason I can’t
give up some of the things

11:42.041 --> 11:44.041
-in this binder for you.
MATT: Thank you.

11:44.041 --> 11:45.792
COLLEEN: Ned, even though
I have had my heart

11:45.792 --> 11:47.792
absolutely set on it,

11:47.792 --> 11:51.458
go ahead and scrap
that dream cake topper.

11:51.458 --> 11:52.750
MATT: You mean the cake topper
that we couldn’t use anyway

11:52.750 --> 11:55.083
because the groom
on it’s black?

11:55.083 --> 11:58.625
I can’t believe I have
to give up my stuff.

11:58.625 --> 12:00.583
I am so sorry
for your loss.

12:00.583 --> 12:01.875
(whimpers)

12:01.875 --> 12:03.333
I don’t mean
to be rude,

12:03.333 --> 12:05.041
but I have
a drag queen funeral

12:05.041 --> 12:06.709
and makeup’s
gonna take forever.

12:08.625 --> 12:10.709
He said he’d do
my makeup, too.

12:11.500 --> 12:13.333
♪

12:13.333 --> 12:16.041
Okay. So with Chad, I was
gonna have roses and lilies,

12:16.041 --> 12:18.250
but I’m ready
to open things up.

12:18.250 --> 12:19.542
-Thank you, thank you.
-Mm-hmm.

12:19.542 --> 12:21.417
Okay. Um, what
about wild flowers?

12:21.417 --> 12:22.333
That’s what I
had when I...

12:22.333 --> 12:24.083
(awkward humming)

12:24.083 --> 12:26.875
What you had when--
when what?

12:26.875 --> 12:28.625
Huh? What I had when I--
when I--when I--

12:28.625 --> 12:29.583
when I was at that
wedding that one time

12:29.583 --> 12:31.834
when--when--when
I got married.

12:31.834 --> 12:33.500
Matt, we have to avoid
those things, too.

12:33.500 --> 12:34.834
That’s the only way
we’ll have a fresh start.

12:34.834 --> 12:36.083
-Agreed, agreed.
-Okay, so we have

12:36.083 --> 12:37.709
to pick things
that neither of us had had.

12:37.709 --> 12:39.166
Okay, okay.

12:39.166 --> 12:40.458
Where do you want
to get married?

12:40.458 --> 12:42.667
Well, Chad and I were
having a church ceremony

12:42.667 --> 12:44.500
with a ballroom
reception, so...

12:44.500 --> 12:46.250
All right, uh, Bonnie
and I had a beach ceremony

12:46.250 --> 12:47.667
with a reception under
the stars, so I think

12:47.667 --> 12:49.208
that we should get
married in the day.

12:49.208 --> 12:51.125
Well, Chad and I were gonna
get married in the daytime.

12:51.125 --> 12:52.625
So we’ll have a wedding
that is neither

12:52.625 --> 12:55.500
in the daytime
nor in the nighttime.

12:55.500 --> 12:59.417
Okay. And not
by the water or on land.

12:59.417 --> 13:01.667
Looks like we’re taking
this wedding to the skies.

13:01.667 --> 13:03.083
I’m afraid of heights.

13:03.083 --> 13:05.291
-I know that.
-Mm-hmm.

13:05.291 --> 13:07.500
JOAN: This is so exciting.

13:07.500 --> 13:09.625
I just can’t wait to hear
your wedding plans.

13:09.625 --> 13:11.917
Well, it wasn’t easy,
but, uh, once we realized

13:11.917 --> 13:13.375
that there were more options
available to us

13:13.375 --> 13:15.083
than we’d
ever imagined,

13:15.083 --> 13:18.000
we found
the perfect location.

13:18.000 --> 13:18.917
Here?

13:18.917 --> 13:21.542
-An elementary school?
-Yeah.

13:21.542 --> 13:22.458
Every little girl

13:22.458 --> 13:24.250
dreams of her
perfect wedding.

13:24.250 --> 13:25.208
And when I was
a little girl,

13:25.208 --> 13:26.417
I went to
elementary school,

13:26.417 --> 13:27.834
so this is the
perfect place.

13:27.834 --> 13:30.250
Yeah. And plus our eighth date
was at a baseball game,

13:30.250 --> 13:32.417
so, I mean, the connection’s
just too strong to ignore.

13:32.417 --> 13:34.875
JOAN: No, you can’t
ignore signs like that.

13:34.875 --> 13:35.834
Just imagine this, right?

13:35.834 --> 13:36.792
Beautiful Wednesday,

13:36.792 --> 13:38.417
sometime between
day and night.

13:38.417 --> 13:39.417
Uh-huh.
After dismissal,

13:39.417 --> 13:40.750
but before
the AA meeting.

13:40.750 --> 13:43.208
Right, and there’s
Mylar balloons everywhere.

13:43.208 --> 13:44.125
And Colleen’s
standing there

13:44.125 --> 13:46.750
with a big, beautiful
bouquet of lollipops.

13:46.750 --> 13:49.458
JOAN: Oh, will there be any
other food besides lollipops?

13:49.458 --> 13:51.333
Because I have
a real problem.

13:51.333 --> 13:55.083
I can’t lick them without
getting really flirty.

13:55.083 --> 13:56.625
COLLEEN: Okay. Yeah,
there’ll be tons of other food,

13:56.625 --> 13:58.500
-anything you could want.
-Yeah, you just have to remember

13:58.500 --> 14:00.750
to cook it and pack it
and bring it.

14:00.750 --> 14:02.750
COLLEEN: So,
what do you think?

14:02.750 --> 14:05.291
A baseball
picnic wedding.

14:05.291 --> 14:06.417
-Cute, right?
-Yeah.

14:06.417 --> 14:08.750
I think...

14:08.750 --> 14:11.875
Maybe it...
I--it’s great.

14:11.875 --> 14:13.792
It’s--it’s--
it’s just great.

14:13.792 --> 14:15.542
Uh, you know,
all that matters is

14:15.542 --> 14:18.375
that you two
are so in love.

14:18.375 --> 14:19.625
COLLEEN: And that
North Tippet Elementary

14:19.625 --> 14:21.041
doesn’t make
the play-offs.

14:21.041 --> 14:22.458
MATT: Yeah.

14:22.458 --> 14:23.375
Yeah.

14:23.375 --> 14:24.792
(children cheering)

14:24.792 --> 14:26.375
COLLEEN: So we’ve decided
if we can’t have a wedding

14:26.375 --> 14:27.709
with all of our
favorite things,

14:27.709 --> 14:29.208
we don’t really want
a wedding at all.

14:29.208 --> 14:30.166
So we’re eloping.

14:30.166 --> 14:31.709
COLLEEN: Some place
neither of us has ever been.

14:31.709 --> 14:32.834
MATT: Yeah, and it
won’t matter what we eat

14:32.834 --> 14:34.709
or what music
we listen to or where we are,

14:34.709 --> 14:36.625
’cause it’s just
gonna be for us.

14:36.625 --> 14:38.417
Oh.

14:38.417 --> 14:40.333
Life is capricious.

14:40.333 --> 14:43.500
One minute, you two are here,
the next you’re gone.

14:43.500 --> 14:46.542
Oh, I’ve got it.
How about Paris?

14:46.542 --> 14:47.458
Oh, my God,
that’s fantastic.

14:47.458 --> 14:48.625
I always wanted
to go to Paris.

14:48.625 --> 14:49.625
That’s where
you were going to go

14:49.625 --> 14:51.417
for your honeymoon
with Chad, isn’t it?

14:51.417 --> 14:53.625
Yes, but I have
a credit.

14:53.625 --> 14:55.667
NED: I also do bachelor parties
if you’re interested.

14:55.667 --> 14:56.834
-Huh.
NED: It’s the one time

14:56.834 --> 14:59.500
I have live prostitutes
in here.

14:59.500 --> 15:00.875
Fun.

15:00.875 --> 15:02.625
♪

15:02.625 --> 15:04.625
This is Charlie Puth’s
dressing room?

15:04.625 --> 15:06.375
Yeah, I just saw him
on the red carpet,

15:06.375 --> 15:08.166
gave him a throat lozenge.

15:08.166 --> 15:09.500
Accidentally
touched my hand.

15:09.500 --> 15:10.333
Don’t touch it!

15:12.792 --> 15:16.917
♪

15:16.917 --> 15:18.583
-Hey, honey.
HEATHER: Hey, sweetie.

15:18.583 --> 15:20.792
Anything fun
happen at school today?

15:20.792 --> 15:21.750
No, unless you count

15:21.750 --> 15:23.792
my entire life
being ruined as fun.

15:23.792 --> 15:25.291
HEATHER: Hey, what--
is this about a boy?

15:25.291 --> 15:27.333
SAM: It was about a boy
until he had his bar mitzvah

15:27.333 --> 15:29.041
last weekend
and didn’t invite me.

15:30.291 --> 15:31.709
So now it’s about a man.

15:32.375 --> 15:33.208
(scoffs)

15:35.041 --> 15:36.625
Joshie dumped Sam?

15:36.625 --> 15:38.291
Oh, I think
it’s Josh now.

15:38.291 --> 15:39.959
(Heather sighs)

15:39.959 --> 15:41.417
HEATHER:
How’s your dinner, Sam?

15:41.417 --> 15:45.166
Tastes like garbage.

15:45.166 --> 15:46.667
Hey, here’s some good news.

15:46.667 --> 15:49.166
I was hired to be
the backstage doctor

15:49.166 --> 15:50.834
at a very special event.

15:50.834 --> 15:52.375
Ooh, that’s so exciting!

15:52.375 --> 15:53.875
Isn’t that exciting! Where?

15:53.875 --> 15:54.834
Oh, I can’t say where.

15:54.834 --> 15:56.542
Doctor-patient
confidentiality.

15:56.542 --> 15:57.583
-Mm.
SOPHIA: But you said

15:57.583 --> 15:59.375
this morning
that if Ms. Stevens

15:59.375 --> 16:01.166
doesn’t die
from her cancer,

16:01.166 --> 16:03.500
she’ll die of
her bad breath.

16:03.500 --> 16:05.875
Oh, yeah, yeah, well,
yeah, I did say that,

16:05.875 --> 16:08.000
but, uh, Ms. Stevens
is very, very sick,

16:08.000 --> 16:10.333
so let’s pretend that I said
that in four to six weeks.

16:10.333 --> 16:13.166
Why is everybody
ganging up on me?

16:13.166 --> 16:14.333
What?

16:14.333 --> 16:15.250
SOPHIA: Huh?

16:15.250 --> 16:16.166
Okay, you know what?

16:16.166 --> 16:19.083
Honey, I think
it’s time to move on.

16:19.083 --> 16:21.291
There are a lot of
wonderful boys out there.

16:21.291 --> 16:24.458
In fact, my friend Gina has
an adorable son named Declan.

16:24.458 --> 16:26.583
SAM: Well, I guess
everybody has something!

16:26.583 --> 16:29.250
Dad has a special event,
Mom has a friend.

16:29.250 --> 16:31.792
Mom’s friend has a son.
Even Sophia has...

16:31.792 --> 16:33.250
SOPHIA: Hormones
she can control?

16:33.250 --> 16:35.667
SAM: I can’t wait until
all of you get dumped!

16:37.917 --> 16:38.834
HEATHER: All right,
what are we gonna do?

16:38.834 --> 16:42.166
She has held this entire family
hostage since Monday.

16:42.166 --> 16:43.250
Now the weekend’s coming.

16:43.250 --> 16:45.291
Parenting is hard.
I don’t want to do it all day.

16:46.750 --> 16:48.250
Okay, look,
the big surprise

16:48.250 --> 16:49.500
I was talking
about at dinner?

16:49.500 --> 16:51.417
-Yeah?
-It’s the Grammys.

16:51.417 --> 16:52.750
-What?
-Yes.

16:52.750 --> 16:55.792
I’m gonna be the backstage
doctor at the Grammys.

16:55.792 --> 16:56.750
I’ll just take Sam.

16:56.750 --> 16:57.875
Oh, honey, you have to.

16:57.875 --> 17:00.792
Oh, that would totally
snap her out of this!

17:00.792 --> 17:01.625
Absolutely.

17:01.625 --> 17:03.500
Who wouldn’t cheer up
hanging backstage

17:03.500 --> 17:06.125
at the Grammys with the
coolest dad in the world?

17:06.125 --> 17:07.917
What are you gonna wear?

17:07.917 --> 17:10.458
♪

17:10.458 --> 17:13.125
SAM: Dad, did you get that
outfit in the women’s section?

17:13.125 --> 17:16.333
No. This is
a men’s rocker outfit.

17:16.333 --> 17:18.250
(distant music, crowd sounds)

17:19.667 --> 17:21.000
Well, I guess
this is a classic case

17:21.000 --> 17:22.959
of "who wore it best."

17:22.959 --> 17:26.500
Come on! We are hanging out
backstage at the Grammys!

17:26.500 --> 17:28.667
There are celebrities
everywhere!

17:28.667 --> 17:30.542
Watch your feet.

17:30.542 --> 17:32.291
Did you see that?
That was a real-life roadie!

17:32.291 --> 17:34.458
Just imagine who
he’s probably toured with!

17:34.458 --> 17:36.792
Man, if those tattoos
could talk.

17:36.792 --> 17:38.959
They’d ask to put
their clothes back on.

17:38.959 --> 17:42.458
All right, I know
what you want.

17:42.458 --> 17:44.083
I was just
gonna warm you up

17:44.083 --> 17:46.125
with the roadie, but I can
see you want the real deal.

17:46.125 --> 17:48.834
Well, guess what?

17:48.834 --> 17:53.417
Dr. Dad knows just where
all the dressing rooms are.

17:53.417 --> 17:54.875
Excuse me, Roadie, where
are the dressing rooms?

17:54.875 --> 17:57.291
Watch your feet.

17:57.291 --> 17:58.834
Probably couldn’t hear
’cause hearing loss,

17:58.834 --> 18:00.291
you know,
touring.

18:00.291 --> 18:02.667
Probably couldn’t hear
you over that jacket.

18:02.667 --> 18:03.709
♪

